@node reqs "An Amiga and..."
@WordWrap
@{jleft}
To use DiskState, you need:
@{lindent 2}
@{b}·@{ub} Kickstart 2.0 or higher.
@endnode

@node usage "This ain't gonna be a nightmare..."
@WordWrap
@{jleft}
@{b}NAME@{ub}@{lindent 8}
DiskState -- Checks if a disk is validated
@{lindent 0}
@{b}INPUTS@{ub}@{lindent 8}
DiskState DISK/A,QUIET/S
@{lindent 4}
@{i}DISK@{ui}
@{lindent 8}The disk you want to check. Can be a name (ie. Work:) or a device name (ie. DH0:).
@{lindent 4}
@{i}QUIET@{ui}
@{lindent 8}No output.
@{lindent 0}
@{b}RETURN CODES@{ub}@{lindent 8}
 0         : Disk is validated or write protected.
 5 (WARN)  : Disk is not validated.
10 (ERROR) : Couldn't get disk information.
@{lindent 0}
@{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}@{lindent 8}
You could have this in your startup-sequence:

C:DiskState dh0: QUIET
IF WARN
    C:MakeDir RAM:ENV RAM:ENV/Sys   ;Disk is unvalidated, putting ENV: into RAM:
    C:Copy >NIL: ENVARC: RAM:ENV ALL NOREQ
    Assign ENV: RAM:ENV
Else
    Assign ENV: DH0:ENV
    C:HDEnv         ;HDEnv is a little utility which updates ENV: from ENVARC:
EndIf
@endnode

